<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="354" pageId="3" pageNumber="353" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1549,2006]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1437,151,536]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="354" pageId="3" pageNumber="353">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,1693,1718]" pageId="3" pageNumber="353">Description</emphasis>
(
<specimenCount box="[357,469,1693,1718]" pageId="3" pageNumber="353" type="female">2 females</specimenCount>
measured). With characteristics of the genus. Body (
<figureCitation box="[1096,1165,1693,1718]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1592,1615]" captionTargetBox="[286,1307,608,1559]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[274,1313,569,1568]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Parapenthus solitarius (Peyron, 1858), female (Ceyhan, Turkey). 1, habitus; 2, left protibia; 3, head; 4, labium. 1–3, dorsal view, 4, ventral view. Scale bars = 1.0 mm (A: Fig. 1; B: Figs 2, 3; C: Fig. 4)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458711/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="353">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) robust, comparatively large, length, according to 
<bibRefCitation box="[462,625,1729,1754]" pageId="3" pageNumber="353" refId="ref13653" refString="Reitter, E. (1900) Bestimmungs-Tabelle der europaischen Coleopteren. XLI. Heft. Enthaltend: Carabidae. Abtheilung: Harpalini und Licinini. Verhandlungen des naturforschenden Vereines in Brunn, 38, 33 - 155. [1899]" type="journal article">Reitter (1900)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<quantity box="[640,765,1730,1754]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="3" pageNumber="353" unit="mm" value="12.5" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="11.0">11–14 mm</quantity>
, and according to our measurements, 12.0– 
<quantity box="[1270,1372,1730,1754]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3699999999999999" pageId="3" pageNumber="353" unit="mm" value="13.7">13.7 mm</quantity>
from apex of clypeus to apex of elytra. Dark reddish-brown, with violet or bluish metallic tinge on dorsum; palpi, antennae and legs light reddish-brown. Head (
<figureCitation box="[692,763,1801,1826]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1592,1615]" captionTargetBox="[286,1307,608,1559]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[274,1313,569,1568]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Parapenthus solitarius (Peyron, 1858), female (Ceyhan, Turkey). 1, habitus; 2, left protibia; 3, head; 4, labium. 1–3, dorsal view, 4, ventral view. Scale bars = 1.0 mm (A: Fig. 1; B: Figs 2, 3; C: Fig. 4)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458711/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="353">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) large (HWmax/PWmax = 0.74–0.75; HWmin/PWmax = 0.60–0.62), with small, convex eyes (HWmax/HWmin = 1.21), tempora long and flat, evenly sloped to neck. Pronotum transverse (PWmax/PL = 1.45–1.47), widest slightly before the middle, markedly narrowed posteriorly (PWmax/PWmin = 1.37–1.43), its sides largely rounded, deeply sinuate in short distance before almost right basal angles; basal margin almost straight, slightly narrower than apical margin and markedly narrower than elytral base. Elytra (EL/EW = 1.37–1.46; EL/PL = 2.34–2.42; EW/PWmax = 1.13–1.18), slightly widened posteriorly, widest slightly after the middle; humerus with a small, acute denticle; basal border complete, slightly sinuate, forming an obtuse angle with lateral margin; striae impressed along entire length; intervals convex, parascutellar striole long, with small basal setigerous pore.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="354" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,536]" box="[199,1411,260,285]" pageId="4" pageNumber="354">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,260,285]" pageId="4" pageNumber="354">Distribution</emphasis>
. This very rare species is known from 
<collectingCountry box="[781,862,260,285]" name="Turkey" pageId="4" pageNumber="354">Turkey</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[873,935,260,285]" name="Syria" pageId="4" pageNumber="354">Syria</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[946,1008,260,285]" name="Israel" pageId="4" pageNumber="354">Israel</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1063,1130,261,285]" name="Egypt" pageId="4" pageNumber="354">Egypt</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation box="[1144,1400,260,284]" pageId="4" pageNumber="354" refId="ref14504" refString="Wrase, D. W. &amp; Kataev, B. M. (2017) Subtribe Ditomina Bonelli, 1810. In: Lobl, I. &amp; Lobl, D. (Eds.), Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera. Vol. 1. Revised and Updated Edition. Archostemata-Myxophaga-Adephaga. Brill, Leiden / Boston, pp. 509 - 514." type="book chapter">Wrase &amp; Kataev 2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,536]" pageId="4" pageNumber="354">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,323,295,320]" pageId="4" pageNumber="354">Bionomics</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation box="[339,502,295,320]" pageId="4" pageNumber="354" refId="ref13577" refString="Peyron, E. (1858) Catalogue des coleopteres des environs de Tarsous (Caramanie) avec la description des especes nouvelle. Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France, Series 3, 6, 353 - 434." type="journal article">Peyron (1858)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned that he found his only specimen “grimpant sur une tige de graminée”, obviously in trying to feed on the seeds.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="354" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,536]" pageId="4" pageNumber="354">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,367,392]" pageId="4" pageNumber="354">Remarks</emphasis>
. The examined specimens of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peyron" baseAuthorityYear="1858" box="[658,917,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Parapenthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="solitarius">
<emphasis box="[658,917,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="354">Parapenthus solitarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are housed in three museum collections and were studied at different times. Unfortunately, during preparation of the present paper, only females were available. The male specimen at 
<collectionCode box="[407,483,440,464]" country="Germany" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34840" name="Staatliches Museum fuer Naturkund Stuttgart" pageId="4" pageNumber="354">SMNS</collectionCode>
was only registered some time ago without examination of the genitalia and now is not accessible. For this reason, the description presented above does not include the characteristics of the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
